notesStmt.note: Fols. 279-80 wanting, replaced with (early modern?) reproductions; Hebraicorum nominum wanting after I
Front flyleaves are four paper followed by one parchment; end flyleaves are paper
Collation note: location of singletons in all quires uncertain

msContents.summary: This manuscript is a thirteenth-century Paris-type Bible with prologues and an incomplete copy of the Interpretationes Hebraicorum nominum (entries for A to H) at the end of the volume.

supportDesc.extent: 124 x 85 mm bound to 132 x 92 mm

p.signatures: Modern signatures in pencil, lower right first recto, perhaps dating to the rebinding of the manuscript

layoutDesc.layout: Two columns of forty-six lines; ruled in lead with vertical bounding lines; written area: 102 x 67 mm

decoDesc.decoNote: Fourteen historiated initials at the beginning of selected books; seventy-six illuminated initials in designs of dragons and foliate patterns in full colors at the beginning of books and some prologues; approximately fifty large red and blue puzzle initials at the beginning of prologues; two-line chapter initials in red or blue with long penwork extensions in the contrasting color; rubrication in red; capitals touched in red; versal initials in Psalms in red or blue; running titles and chapter numbers in alternately red and blue letters
1rHistoriated initial F, Jerome in his study
4vHistoriated initial I, Seven days of Creation and Crucifixion
117rIlluminated initial F, Benaiah beheading the Amalekite
248rHistoriated initial B, King David with harp
276rHistoriated initial P, King Solomon with rod and youth
316rHistoriated initial V, Isaiah being sawn in two
421vHistoriated initial E, Mattathias beheading an idolater
495rHistoriated initial P, Paul and two Jews
548rHistoriated initial A, Saint John the Evangelist

binding.p: Rebound in 1985 in tan Nigerian goat skin and blindtooled, with accompanying slipcover

history.provenance: Formerly owned by the Farrell family (near Hull, England); acquired at auction in 1984
